<span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is the global alliance comprised of three Global/International agencies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he World Blind Union (WBU), </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">International Council for Education of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">People with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Visual Impair</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ICEVI) and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">International Agency for the Prevention of Blindness (IAPB). The main objective of this alliance is to achieve convergence and maximise the impact on the lives of persons with visual disabilities without duplicating the efforts made by each agency in their specific areas of expertise. With several hundred members globally, each agency has specific areas of expertise and experience towards promoting empowerment, inclusion, development, promotion and protection of all human rights and fundamental freedoms of persons with visual disabilities. The ICEVI focuses on education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> IAPB specialises in eye health</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> prevention of avoidable blindness</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and advancing the rights of the visually impaired</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and the WBU </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">works to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ensure effective representation and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">full </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">participation of persons with visual disabilities in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">actions and processes of various agencies at national, regional and global levels</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> through a wide range of actions including advocacy and campaigning. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">VA wholeheartedly welcomes and sincerely appreciates the enquiry of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK parliament </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">International Development Select Committee (IDSC) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, which seeks to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> find</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">out how it can improve the inclusion of disability in the work of DFID and invit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> written submission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> from NGOs and other relevant stakeholders.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Poverty </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is inextricably linked to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">disability in general</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and visual disability in particular . </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">overty and visual </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">disability reinforce each other</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> . Poor persons are most likely to become blind/</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">artially sighted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lind/</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">artially sighted persons are most likely to become poorer. Higher dependency on family members</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> lack of independent mobility</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">accessible transport</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and buildings; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an absence of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> information in accessible formats  such as Braille, large print, audio, electronic, DAISY </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(Digital Audio Information System) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">further</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> reduce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">access to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">education, health care, livelihoods and recreation. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hronic poverty conditions, low literacy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">apathy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">within </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the family</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> negative</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> community</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> attitudes towards persons with visual disabilities, and barriers in accessing adequate food and nutrition ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> posed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> serious threat to the right to life of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lind/</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">artially sighted persons</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This can be seen in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">high rates of infant mortality, infanticide, starv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ation and unnatural deaths. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There should be universal prohibition of abortion  based on the pre-natal diagnosis of a disability. The right to life as a full member of society is integral to the realization of all the rights set down in the Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities (CRPD) and other human rights instruments.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ack of rehabilitation and support services; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">accessible transport system</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;  chronic poverty conditions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and negative attitudes towards persons with visual disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> prevent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> them from accessing rehabilitation services including assistive devices, technology and support services </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">maximise their potential and cope with their impairment. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Around 500,000 children become blind each year. Many of the conditions associated with childhood blindness are also causes of child mortality (e.g. premature birth, measles, congenital rubella syndrome, vitamin A deficiency, and meningitis).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Education is one of the fundamental and basic human rights enshrined in various UN instruments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Yet</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> unfortunately persons with visual disabilities  have fewer chances of accessing quality education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> due to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lack of adequate support services </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">trained teachers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inaccessible </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">teaching and learning materials  in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mainstream </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">schools;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> nonexistence of special schools  in rural areas; increased vulnerability to sexual and physical abuse in residential schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">located in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">urban areas;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> negative attitudes, fear and apathy of family members towards persons with visual disabilities. In developing countries, less than 10% of blind children get to go to school, hence the need for inclusive education </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> all programs with appropriate resources and support.  Access to assistive devices and technology is a distant dream for persons with visual disabilities due to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a lack of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">availability, affordability and negative attitudes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">family members. This has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">limited the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">functional abilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of persons with visual disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and contributed to their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dependency and isolation.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Persons with visual disabilities have very low health outcomes as a result of lack of health care services, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">low </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">level</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of awareness </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as well as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">apathy of health care personnel. They have increased risk and vulnerability to morbidity, mortality, communicable and non</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">communicable diseases, HIV infection and other sexually transmitted diseases. Lack of access to accessible information on general</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> health</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, eye</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> health</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, sexual and reproductive health further contribute </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">very low health outcomes. Health personnel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">poorly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">equipped to deal with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">specific needs of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ersons with visual disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; and moreover, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">training programmes on health care </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tend to be in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">accessible to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">persons with visual disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">since they are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">often</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> based on visual media to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">meet</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the needs of rural population</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s who often have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">low</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">er</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> literacy rate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">state </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">health care system  and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">development agencies’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">health programmes   often ignore the promotion  of eye health care, prevention of avoidable blindness and retention of residual eyesight. This has contributed to high rates of avoidable blindness (approximately 80% of a total of 285 million people, according to WHO statistics released in 2010). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Experience during recent humanitarian emergencies has revealed that existing emergency preparedness measures are not adequately meeting the needs of blind and partially sighted persons and that mainstream emergency aid providers are ill-prepared to address their needs.   All relevant stakeholders need to ensure that their emergency preparedness plans consider the unique needs of blind and partially sighted persons.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID’s paper </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">en</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">titled “Poverty, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">isability and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evelopment” </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">February 2000</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> clearly articulated the close links between poverty and disability. It re-affirms the commit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to include persons with visual disabilities in all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">actions and processes  through</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> twin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">track approach. This approach mandates  stakeholders to implement disability specific interventions in order to address the specific needs and issues of persons with visual disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">insists on ensuring the effective and meaningful inclusion of persons with disabilities in all general development programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">increase</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> access and participation of persons with visual disabilities in all aspects of life in society. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Vision Alliance commends</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> government in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> efforts to promote disability inclusion within the post 2015 framework, so that no one is left behind, and encourages </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to promote the disaggregation of data by disability in these processes and bilaterally. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Vision Alliance makes the following suggestions on the basis of the above stated facts in order to enhance the participation, representation and accessibility of persons with visual disabilities in DFID’s work:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Appointment or designati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on of a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> disability focal person or advisor in line with other thematic advisors at all levels;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Formulation of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">strategy for the inclusion of persons with visual disabilities in all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">actions and processes  with the active involvement of persons with visual disabilities and their representative organisations;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Funding guidelines should expressly state</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the inclusion of persons with visual disabilities is mandatory;</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Call</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for proposals and proposal formats should be inclusive of persons with visual disabilities;</span></li></ul><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Procurement polic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> should insist on accessible tools, systems, equipment, literature, assistive devices and technology including  information technology such as Braille </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and other tactile </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">markings, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">audio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, DAISY, large print, electronic text </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">etc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Fair opportunities for persons with visual disabilities in the recruitment process at all levels;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Massive intensive capacity building programmes for representative organisations of persons with visual disabilities in order to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">assist them to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">influence the state and DFID country programmes for effective inclusion of persons with visual disabilities.</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Financial and technical support to organisations  of persons with visual disabilities in order to develop workable models on education, rehabilitation, eye health care, livelihoods</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to promote </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wider replication by influencing the state and other key </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">stakeholders</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">All health care programmes should be inclusive of persons with visual disabilities in terms of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> both</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> primary stakeholders and beneficiaries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> so that persons with disabilities adequately benefit from health programming across the range of health care needs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> including but not limited to pre- and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">post</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-natal schemes, prevention of communicable and non-communicable diseases; and across the health continuum from prevention</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">promotion to rehabilitation and care. This should include attention to the provision and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">promotion of eye health care and prevention of avoidable blindness along with retention of residual sight.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">All development programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> both disability-specific and general</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> should make provision of information in accessible formats such as Braille, large print, audio, DAISY, electronic and others</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in order to inform persons with visual disabilities about the programme. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">While welcoming recent commitments </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that DFID-funded schools must be accessible, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we recommend that this should include a requirement for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">all educational programmes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> inclusive of persons with visual disabilities through the provision of accessib</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">le</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">buildings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">textbooks , </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">teaching and learning materials, and evaluation systems; and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> training teachers in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">teaching children with visual disabilities. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">All emergency interventions should be inclusive of persons with visual disabilities through audio warning systems, support during </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rescue, relief, rehabilitation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and long</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> term reconstruction initiatives. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Adoption of a twin-track approach in order to address the specific needs and issues of persons with visual disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and ensure inclusion in general development programmes through the implementation of disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">specific interventions as well as inclusion in general development programmes.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">All development programmes addressing issues of water, sanitation, housing and livelihoods should be inclusive of persons with visual disabilities and should address the specific issues of accessibility and proximity to access</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ible</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> services;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘Nothing about us, without us’: participation of persons with disabilities, including those with vis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ual</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> disabilities and their representative organisations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in development projects from design to implementation and evaluation will be essential to understand </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">needs and consider the best ways to promote inclusion and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">monitor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> impact. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Better information is a necessity to ensure disability is adequately attended to. Appropriate accountability mechanisms are crucial</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> including monitoring projects with disaggregated indicators to better understand the impact on persons with disabilities;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">All DFID’s policies and partnership agreements should reflect all of the above and staff should be trained on disability inclusion, so that it is firmly embedded in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DFID’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>